<p><i><b>Collapse: How Societies Choose to Fail or Succeed</b></i> is a 2005 book by <a href="/wiki/Jared_Diamond" title="Jared Diamond">Jared M. Diamond</a>, <a href="/wiki/Professor" title="Professor">professor</a> of <a href="/wiki/Geography" title="Geography">geography</a> and <a href="/wiki/Physiology" title="Physiology">physiology</a> at <a href="/wiki/University_of_California,_Los_Angeles" title="University of California, Los Angeles">University of California, Los Angeles</a>. Diamond's book deals with "<a href="/wiki/Societal_collapse" title="Societal collapse">societal collapses</a> involving an <a href="/wiki/Environment_(biophysical)" title="Environment (biophysical)">environmental</a> component, and in some cases also contributions of <a href="/wiki/Climate_change" title="Climate change">climate change</a>, hostile neighbors, and <a href="/wiki/International_trade" title="International trade">trade partners</a>, plus questions of societal responses" (p. 15). In writing the book Diamond intended that its readers should learn from <a href="/wiki/History" title="History">history</a> (p. 23).</p>
